flow.example:
// Create a todo list with:
// - Input to add new todos
// - Each todo has a delete button
// - Can't add empty todos
// - Show "No todos yet" when list is empty
// - Clear input after adding

flow.mentorSays:
Perfect! Here's the optimal solution approach:

```javascript
function TodoList() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);
  const [input, setInput] = useState('');

  const addTodo = () => {
    if (!input.trim()) return;
    setTodos([...todos, { id: Date.now(), text: input }]);
    setInput('');
  };

  const removeTodo = (id) => {
    setTodos(todos.filter(todo => todo.id !== id));
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input value={input} onChange={e => setInput(e.target.value)} />
      <button onClick={addTodo}>Add</button>
      {todos.length === 0 ? (
        <p>No todos yet</p>
      ) : (
        <ul>
          {todos.map(todo => (
            <li key={todo.id}>
              {todo.text}
              <button onClick={() => removeTodo(todo.id)}>Delete</button>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

This solution demonstrates best practices for React development and shows how to properly implement Array manipulation, state updates.

